  2. Write a function that calculates the ratio of the mean and the median of a given vector.
mean_by_median <- function(v) {
  ## omit na?
  mean(v) / median(v)
}
  1. Write a function that ignores the lowest and the highest value from a given vector and calculate the mean.
mean_noextreme <- function(v) {
  mean(sort(v)[c(-1:-length(v))])
}

Task 7 - Basic visualization with R

  1. Compare the distributions of the body heights of the two species from the ‘magic_guys.csv’ dataset graphically
  2. using the basic ‘hist’ function as well as ‘ggplot’ and ‘geom_histogram’ functions from the ggplot2 package. Optimize the plots for example by trying several different ‘breaks’. Note that ggplot2-based functions give you many more options for changing the visualization parameters, try some of them.
magic_guys <- read.csv('data/magic_guys.csv')
height2plot <- magic_guys |> group_by(species) |> select(length)
ggplot(height2plot, aes(x = length, color = species)) +
  geom_histogram() + theme_classic()

2. Do the same comparison as in a. but with boxplots. If you want to use the ggplot2-package, use the functions ‘ggplot’ and ‘geom_boxplot’.

ggplot(height2plot, aes(y = length, color = species)) +
  geom_boxplot() + theme_classic()

3. Find the genes for which there are more than X% (X=10%, 20%, 50%) missing values.

napercent <- colSums(is.na(microa))/colSums(microa, na.rm=T)
fifty_genes <- colnames(microa)[napercent>0.5]
twenty_genes <- colnames(microa)[napercent>0.2]
ten_genes <- colnames(microa)[napercent>0.1]

microa.impute <- sapply(microa, function(x) {x[is.na(x)]=mean(x, na.rm=T)})
